[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":751},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-47-understanding-prototypes\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-47-understanding-prototypes\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-47-understanding-prototypes\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-47-understanding-prototypes\u002F":726,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-47-understanding-prototypes\u002F":735},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190521\u002F3439501601\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":710,"date":711,"description":712,"extension":713,"lang":714,"meta":715,"navigation":268,"path":716,"readingMinutes":717,"seo":718,"standalone":719,"stem":720,"tags":721,"tldr":723,"updated":711,"url":724,"__hash__":725},"content\u002Fen\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjsweirdworld-47-understanding-prototypes.md","[JS Weird World] No.47 Understanding Prototypes","1000324682",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":705},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,43,50,53,58,71,76,85,90,93,98,108,113,116,121,131,137,142,149,154,157,307,314,455,461,475,680,685,688,692,701],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"JavaScript uses prototypal inheritance, which means there's this thing called a prototype.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"understanding-prototypes","Understanding Prototypes",[17,25,26],{},"First off, we know objects can have properties and methods, and we can use the dot operator to grab a property or method. In JavaScript every object and every function has a prototype property, and that property references another object — usually called proto.",[17,28,29,30,34,35,38,39,42],{},"Say we've got an object ",[31,32,33],"code",{},"obj"," with a property called ",[31,36,37],{},"prop1"," on it. We can grab it with ",[31,40,41],{},"obj.prop1",".",[17,44,45],{},[46,47],"img",{"alt":48,"src":49},"diagram","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FGvbj9dX.png",[17,51,52],{},"In JavaScript, every object and function has a prototype property.",[17,54,55],{},[46,56],{"alt":48,"src":57},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FujtvRes.png",[17,59,60,61,64,65,67,68,42],{},"That property references another object, which we call proto. And proto can have its own properties too — say ",[31,62,63],{},"prop2"," — so when we want to grab ",[31,66,63],{}," we can just write ",[31,69,70],{},"obj.prop2",[17,72,73],{},[46,74],{"alt":48,"src":75},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FVq3wUOQ.png",[17,77,78,79,81,82,84],{},"When we use the dot operator to grab ",[31,80,63],{}," off ",[31,83,33],{},", it won't find it directly, so it goes looking in the prototype.",[17,86,87],{},[46,88],{"alt":48,"src":89},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FGGjQY6t.png",[17,91,92],{},"And that prototype object can point to yet another object.",[17,94,95],{},[46,96],{"alt":48,"src":97},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FoW5l7hH.png",[17,99,100,101,104,105,42],{},"Every object can have its own prototype, so when this proto has a ",[31,102,103],{},"prop3"," on it, we can grab it with ",[31,106,107],{},"obj.prop3",[17,109,110],{},[46,111],{"alt":48,"src":112},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fluirq2S.png",[17,114,115],{},"This whole process is like a chain, which is why it's called the prototype chain. Just don't mix it up with the scope chain — they look similar, but the scope chain is about finding variables you can access, while the prototype chain is about finding properties and methods.",[17,117,118],{},[46,119],{"alt":48,"src":120},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FjLE3x65.png",[17,122,123,124,127,128,130],{},"Normally this proto is hidden, which is why we don't have to write ",[31,125,126],{},"obj.proto.proto.prop3"," — just ",[31,129,107],{}," is enough.",[17,132,133,134,136],{},"But here's a fun situation in JavaScript: if we have a second ",[31,135,33],{},", it can point to the same prototype.",[17,138,139],{},[46,140],{"alt":48,"src":141},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FwonD10e.png",[17,143,144,145,148],{},"So when we call ",[31,146,147],{},"obj2.prop2",", it'll return the same spot.",[17,150,151],{},[46,152],{"alt":48,"src":153},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FNj43kat.png",[17,155,156],{},"And that's basically the whole concept of prototypes and the prototype chain. Keep it simple — it's just a special reference hanging off our object. Now let's jump straight into an example.",[158,159,164],"pre",{"className":160,"code":161,"language":162,"meta":163,"style":163},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var person = {\n  firstname: 'Default',\n  lastname: 'Default',\n  getFullName: function() {\n    return this.firstname + ' ' + this.lastname;\n  }\n}\n\nvar john = {\n  firstname: 'John',\n  lastname: 'Doe',\n}\n","js","",[31,165,166,185,198,208,224,251,257,263,270,282,292,302],{"__ignoreMap":163},[167,168,171,175,179,182],"span",{"class":169,"line":170},"line",1,[167,172,174],{"class":173},"sWyjQ","var",[167,176,178],{"class":177},"sMAXC"," person ",[167,180,181],{"class":173},"=",[167,183,184],{"class":177}," {\n",[167,186,188,191,195],{"class":169,"line":187},2,[167,189,190],{"class":177},"  firstname: ",[167,192,194],{"class":193},"sTRMh","'Default'",[167,196,197],{"class":177},",\n",[167,199,201,204,206],{"class":169,"line":200},3,[167,202,203],{"class":177},"  lastname: ",[167,205,194],{"class":193},[167,207,197],{"class":177},[167,209,211,215,218,221],{"class":169,"line":210},4,[167,212,214],{"class":213},"sj_SG","  getFullName",[167,216,217],{"class":177},": ",[167,219,220],{"class":173},"function",[167,222,223],{"class":177},"() {\n",[167,225,227,230,234,237,240,243,246,248],{"class":169,"line":226},5,[167,228,229],{"class":173},"    return",[167,231,233],{"class":232},"sCcAr"," this",[167,235,236],{"class":177},".firstname ",[167,238,239],{"class":173},"+",[167,241,242],{"class":193}," ' '",[167,244,245],{"class":173}," +",[167,247,233],{"class":232},[167,249,250],{"class":177},".lastname;\n",[167,252,254],{"class":169,"line":253},6,[167,255,256],{"class":177},"  }\n",[167,258,260],{"class":169,"line":259},7,[167,261,262],{"class":177},"}\n",[167,264,266],{"class":169,"line":265},8,[167,267,269],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":268},true,"\n",[167,271,273,275,278,280],{"class":169,"line":272},9,[167,274,174],{"class":173},[167,276,277],{"class":177}," john ",[167,279,181],{"class":173},[167,281,184],{"class":177},[167,283,285,287,290],{"class":169,"line":284},10,[167,286,190],{"class":177},[167,288,289],{"class":193},"'John'",[167,291,197],{"class":177},[167,293,295,297,300],{"class":169,"line":294},11,[167,296,203],{"class":177},[167,298,299],{"class":193},"'Doe'",[167,301,197],{"class":177},[167,303,305],{"class":169,"line":304},12,[167,306,262],{"class":177},[17,308,309,310,313],{},"Here we've got two objects, and we're going to set ",[31,311,312],{},"john","'s prototype. But seriously, don't ever do this in real code — it's purely to make the concept easy to understand.",[158,315,317],{"className":160,"code":316,"language":162,"meta":163,"style":163},"var person = {\n  firstname: 'Default',\n  lastname: 'Default',\n  getFullName: function() {\n    return this.firstname + ' ' + this.lastname;\n  }\n}\n\nvar john = {\n  firstname: 'John',\n  lastname: 'Doe',\n}\n\u002F\u002F Never use this approach in real project work — it's only here to help understand prototypes.\njohn.__proto__ = person;\nconsole.log(john.getFullName());\n",[31,318,319,329,337,345,355,373,377,381,385,395,403,411,415,422,437],{"__ignoreMap":163},[167,320,321,323,325,327],{"class":169,"line":170},[167,322,174],{"class":173},[167,324,178],{"class":177},[167,326,181],{"class":173},[167,328,184],{"class":177},[167,330,331,333,335],{"class":169,"line":187},[167,332,190],{"class":177},[167,334,194],{"class":193},[167,336,197],{"class":177},[167,338,339,341,343],{"class